{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999627/1938010801/0204.xml":{"full_text":"2\n\ntt\nsat\n_msmtolg *m\nTHE WOES OF THE WORKER have more appeal to 17\nyear-old Marian Hepburn than the loads of fan mail that are 1\na tribute to the talent of her older sister, Katharine Hep\nburn, the stage and screen star. The younger Miss Hep\nburn has come here from Bennington College in Vermont to\ntake a temporary job at the United Federal Workers School\nat 532 17th-st nw.\nShe is a student of worker education.\n9\nto\n4:30\nU. S. Unfair to Aides,\nIs Magazine Charge\nI\nBy ALFRED FRIENDLY\n\"Statements of enlightened personnel policy or broad legal guarantees of\ncivil rights to Government workers are not sufficient to prevent governmental\nemployers from pursuing policies forbidden to employers in private industry\nUnless machinery is devised to curb the power of public authorities to inter\nfere with the free organization of their employes thru their practically un\nlimited power to discipline, the laws guarantees will mean but little.\u201d\nThus write Sterling D. Spero and Samuel Paul Puner in the current issue\nof The Nation. In their article, \"Uncle Sam, Privileged Boss,\u201d they imply, by\nciting an imposing list of cases, that the Federal Government indulges in\nanti-union discrimination, fosters company unions, denies redress to ag\ngrieved employes and finally, that its grounds for believing \u201cmilitant tactics\nhave no place in the functions of any organization of Government em\nployes\u201d are invalid.\nTwo Simple Cases\nThe cases of Jonathan Levine, New York postal clerk, and of Bernard\nSchultz and William Greenberg. Baltimore Social Security Board employes,\nare cited to prove anti-union discrimination. The list could be enlarged.\nThe tacts, however, are subject to various interpretations.\nOne may be\nheve with Spero and Puner. that the Government is anti-union. One may\nbelieve that it is no such thing and that the discharged employes were union\nmembers only coincidentallv. Or one may believe that certain Government\nofficials\u2014the ones responsible for the specific persons' discharges\u2014are anti\nunion\nSo with the accusation that the Government fosters company unions. One\nmay or may not choose to consider, with The Nation's authors, the Depart\nment of Agricultures Employe Activity Council, and Labor's Conciliation\nCommittee 'and for that matter the I. D. R. A. in Ickes\u2019 bailiwick) as\ncompany-union manifestations. It all depends on how you look at it.\nCertainly there can be no argument, however, with the contention that\nan aggrieved employe, or one discriminated against, has not as adequate a\nmeans of redress as the employe in private industry, who may present his\nrase to the NLRB\nThe agreements to submit controversial cases in the\nFederal service to an arbitrator's decision have resulted only from the good\nwill and good judgment of the employer. The employe has no assurance\nthat another case will get the same treatment.\nIn tiie absence of a per\nmanent agency to settle grievances impartially, the only thing an employe\nan do is hope\nNovel Argument\nMost novel of Spero and Puner\u2019s points, however, is the argument that the\nGovernments traditional policy of expecting special employe relations has\nno justification. That policy is based, the article continues. (1) on the ne\ncessity of sovereignty, i2i the exceptional social importance of the Gov\neminent s functions and (3) the impartial or neutral character of its services.\nBut the governmental activities, administrative, industrial, service and law\nenforcement. parallel. compete with or supplement non-governmental ac\ntivities Certainly there is nothing in the character of these services\nto justify the Government's claim for special consideration as an employer.\u201d\nEven the function of law enforcement is \"dependent on the smooth running\nof the social machine. New York or Chicago could not be policed at night\nif private indu-trv did not keep the lights on If the governmental\nagency can insist on special privileges nere which would restrict the civil\nrights of its employes, including the right to strike, its claims can logically\nbe extended to all employes in socially vital industries. The definition of a\nwcally vital industry can obviously be almost indefinitely extended until the\nworking class has been stripped of its defenses.\u201d\n2000 Temporary Jobs\nTwo thousand employes. from Civil Service rolls, are being employed on a\ntemporary three months basis in the Baltimore Social Security Board offices,\nit was announced yesterday. Pressure to speed up settlement of unemploy\nwant compensation claims necessitated the increase.\nNew Courses Announced\nThe P. F w A announces six new courses for the second semester of its\nFederal Workers' School. They include psychology, photography, ballroom\ndancing, a symposium on consumers' problems conducted by Agriculture Con\nsumer Counsel Donald Montgomery, literature taught by Novelist Floyd Dell,\nand a course i journalism under the direction of Delbert Clark, Washington\nbureau manager of The New York Times.\nAUTO LOANS\nPrecured In S Minutes!\nOpen 9 A N to 9 P M\nCOlumbia Wk\nAmple Parking\nAUTO MART\n2305 Georgia Ave. N W.\n\nNazis Hit at Jews\n1 NUREMBERG, Germany, Jan. 8\u2014\nJews were forbidden today to use mu\nnicipal tub and shower baths. They\nhave been banned from municipal\nswimming pools since 1933.\nSuspect Held\nas \u2018Bootleg\nKing\n9\nArraignment before Commissioner\nTurnage was scheduled today for\nRalph Marcantoni, 38, arrested last i\nnight by United States deputies at\nthe request of District police, who ac\ncuse him of being the leader of an\nillicit liquor ring uncovered Tuesday\nnight by a raid at 16th and Madison\nstreets nw where two huge stills were\nconfiscated.\nMarcantoni. who gave Baltimore as\nhis address, is said by police to have\nbeen one of the bigger shots in illicit\nliquor traffic during the prohibition\nera. He was arrested when he came\nhere to answer a traffic violation\ncharge, accompanying another charge\nlodged against him Oct. 29, 1936.\nwhen he was arrested here with\nhis wife in another liquor raid. He\nwas accused then of Federal liquor\ntax violation.\nThe 16th-st raid was one of the\nlargest; hauls made in recent months.\nAt the large colonial home officers\nfound two stills, one of 300 gallons\ncapacity, and arrested Mazzeraino\nMagnaterra after seizing a 16-year\nold boy in a liquor laden auto earlier\nin the day.\nFour hundred gallons of liquor,\n1350 gallons of mash and other ma\nterials were seized in the raid.\nWaitress Fatally Beaten\nDETROIT, Jan. 8 Police today\nsearched for clues in the fatal beat\ning of a young woman, identified as'\na former beer garden waitress, Emma\nL. Mahn, 22, found slain in a field.'\nA junkman, John Gwozdz, 64. discov\nered the body. The girl's face had.\nbeen bruised and her body showed\nsigns of a struggle.\nI\nRecession May Bring\nRelief Policy Change\nBy HERBERT LITTLE\nThe recession is threatening to bring a demand for\nprofound changes in Federal relief policies.\nThe Senate Unemployment Committee, after two\nmore weeks of hearings, will be in a position to make a\npreliminary report about the time President Roosevelt\nsends up his relief message.\nChairman Byrnes (D.. S. C.), in his\u2019\nquestions thru the opening week of\nthe inquiry, has indicated deep in\nterest in possibilities of the relief load\nbeing carried henceforth thru Social\nSecurity agencies, plus state and local\ndirect-relief operations.\nWOULD KILL JOB RELIEF\nIf such a project were carried out.\nWPA's work-relief program would be\nabolished.\nWork relief under WPA\ncosts about twice as much as the so\ncalled dole, but its defenders point\nto several compensating factors: (1)\nprojects of permanent economic value.\n(2) work for \u201cidle hands,\" and (3)\nstimulation of heavy industries thru\npurchase of materials.\nAny alternative to WPA probably\nwould include large Federal grants\nto the states, to aid in their direct\nrelief programs.\nAnother possibility\nis Federal subsidies to augment the\nunemployment insurance funds, al\nready functioning in 20-odd states.\nChairman Byrnes has indicated\nthat the initial three-week hearings\nwill concentrate upon the immediate\nslump. Next week s witnesses include\nLammot Du Pont, John L. Lewis,\nPresident Benjamin Fairless of U. S.\nSteel, Secretary of Agriculture Wal\nlace, President J. J. Pelley of the\nAssociation of American Railroads,\nPresident A. F. Whitney of the\nBrotherhood of Railway Trainmen,\nand other important industrialists.\nThen the inquiry will recess for two\nor three weeks, and resume in Feb\nruary to discuss long-range affects of\nunemployment. One of the factors\nto be examined is the extent of\nmachine displacement of\nlabor.\nhuman\nCOYLE IS ENGAGED\nTo aid in the long-range study, the\ncommittee has retained as consultant\nDavid Cushman Coyle. industrial\nengineer noted for his advocacy of\nheavy spending and taxing.\nByrnes contended yesterday that\nco-operation would dissipate a lack\nof confidence described by some wit\nnesses as a contributing cause of the\nbusiness recession. Byrnes suggested\nthat the various groups get together\nand confer on general economic con\nditions.\nOther developments in the attempt\nto alleviate the business recession\nwere:\n1. Congressional farm leaders\nMartin McBohin displays his taped tag.\nNew York Motorists Balk at Licenses\nAdvertising 1939 World\u2019s Fair\nBy United Press\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8\u2014Grover A. Whalen, smooth\ntalking master mind of the 1939 World\u2019s Fair, defied\na swarm of angry motorists today and insisted they\nshould be happy to use license plates publicizing his fair.\nWhalen, president of the World\u2019s*\nFair Corp., was disturbed because\nauto owners objected to the inscrip\ntion \u201cNew York World\u2019s Fair 1939\"\non New York State license plates\nfor 1938.\npointed to pending bills providing\nfor the\ncreation of laboratories to\ndevelop new uses for agricultural\nproducts. Henry Ford, in an inter\nview yesterday, suggested this same\nmeans as a way to absorb surpluses\nand create additional employment.\n2. Sen. Lewis B. Schwellenbach (D.,\nWash.) laid before President Roose\nvelt a proposal to expand the Works\nProgress Administration to absorb all\nidle persons.\n3. Sen. William Murray (D.. Mont.),\nsupported proposals by President Wil\nliam Green of the American Federa\ntion of Labor that WPA be expanded\nto provide for the idle and that the\nPWA program be enlarged.\nWhen You Need Furniture\nDRIVE OVER THE\nANACOSTIA RIVER\nand\nSAVE\nat THOMPSON BROS.\nFurniture, Stoves, Floor Coverings,\nRadios, Etc.\n1220-1226 Good Hope Road\n27 YEARS IN\nANACOSTIA, D. C.\nYOUR LUCK!!!\ne\nI PRICE\n40W\nSALE\n4\u2018.\ne\nD.J. KAUFMAN, Inc.\n1744 PA. 4U 2005 FA AYL\nMartin McBohin, an Irishman with\na temper and a former Marine\nsergeant, faced a possible maximum\npenalty of 30 days in jail and a\n$50 fine for placing a piece of ad\nhesive tape over the advertisement on\nhis plates.\nScores of motorists threatened to\nduplicate McBohin\u2019s action.\nOne\nyoung woman, described as a \u201cred\nhead\u201d told a clerk: \u201cI\u2019m not going to\nadvertise the World s Fair or any\nother commodity fiee of charge. If\nthey want the advertising, they can\npay me.\nI'm telling you, I have a\nlarge can of black paint home.\nIt\nwon\u2019t take me more than a couple\nof minutes to get rid of this World\u2019s\nFair business.\u201d\n1\nI\n10004\nG. W. KING, JR.\n511 11th St.N. W.\nKS ANTOL\nya CAPSULES\nfir\nI G\nI\nWill\nFOR\nperiodic pain;\ndoes not up\nset stomach.\nPAIN\n25c and 50c\nSERVICE PHARMACY\nJ\n18 People\nAfter a Range\n1\n1\nWhen Mrs. J. L. Fisk\nplaced this little ad in\nThe News to sell her\nrange, 18 people replied.\n\u201cI advertised it in The\nNews exclusively,\u201d Mrs.\nFisk proudly stated.\nELECTRIC RANGE (General Elec\ntric). u.sed month: 3 burner.* and\ndeep well. Bargain. WIs. 2761-J.\nThe News\u2019 rate is the I\nlowest in town\u2014only 3c\na word.\nDistrict 7777\nI","height":"21212","width":"14444"}}
